{#-
  MARKER FIXTURE - Phase 13 constant-propagation: a dangerous identifier held in a
  {% set %} variable. Each dunder is bound to a variable and reached via subscript, so the
  subscript KEY is a `Name` (a load), not a `Const` - neither the Phase-4..10 fold nor the
  taint walk (both `Const`-only) can see the dunder it stands for, so Phase 2..12 MISS this.

  Phase 13 substitutes constant-string {% set %} variables into their loads BEFORE the fold
  (a single deterministic pass over a copy; never evaluates or renders), so
  `cycler[i][g]` becomes `cycler['__init__']['__globals__']` and the existing identifier-only
  walk fires. It also covers propagate-THEN-fold: `a + b` of two propagated consts folds to
  a single dunder (`'__re' + 'duce__'` -> `'__reduce__'`, a Phase-12 catalog name).
      cycler -> __init__ -> __globals__   (vars i, g)
      obj    -> __reduce__                (vars a + b, folded after propagation)
      target -> __class__                 (var c)

  HARMLESS (MARKER only): parsed + walked, never rendered; constant
  propagation is a static AST rewrite - no string is evaluated. The dangerous SIGNAL is the
  resolved dunder chain, not the harmless 'cycler'/'obj'/'target' identifiers.
  Sources: PayloadsAllTheThings (SSTI/Jinja2 variable-held identifier obfuscation); CWE-94 / CWE-1336.
-#}
{% for m in messages %}{{ m.role }}: {{ m.content }}
{% endfor %}{% set i = '__init__' %}{% set g = '__globals__' %}{% set a = '__re' %}{% set b = 'duce__' %}{% set c = '__class__' %}{{ cycler[i][g] }}{{ obj[a + b] }}{{ target[c] }}
